Jari has pitched camp at Kapsait since October last year, already fulfilling his dream of training with the world’s best distance runners at their home turf. 

In an exclusive interview with Nation Sport this week, Jari said when he set foot at Kapsait, he found a training programme quite different from what he was used to back at home, and is happy his performance has improved tremendously, confident he will lower his personal best time from 2:14:02 - clocked in Durban two-and-a-half years ago - to 2:07, or even 2:06 after his stint at Kapsait. 






Jari Munyaradzi (centre), a marathoner from Zimbabwe, who is camping at Kapsait Nike Athletics Training Camp in Elgeyo Marakwet County, the women’s World Marathon Record Holder Brigid Kosgei (left) and Geoffrey Kipsang, Brigid’s pacemaker, train on the Moi’s Bridge-Kachibora road in Trans Nzoia County on January 19, 2021. Jari is preparing to get a slot in their national team to the Tokyo Olympics.
Photo credit: Jared Nyataya | Nation Media Group

 

His other distance personal best times are 48:59 (15 kilometres) and 1:05:08 (half marathon), both clocked in Durban, South Africa, in 2009 and 2012, respectively. 

He will be looking forward to compete in one of the marathon races in a bid to get a qualification mark to compete at the Tokyo Olympics Games’ marathon race in Sapporo in August as a stepping stone to next year’s World Championships in Eugene. 



